context: <b5_0>Poultry<b5_0/> (/ˌpoʊltriː/) are domesticated birds <a0_0>kept by humans <b10_0>for the eggs they produce, their meat, their feathers, or sometimes as pets<b10_0/>.<a0_0/> These birds are most typically members of the superorder <b7_0>Galloanserae<b7_0/> (fowl), especially the order Galliformes (which includes <a2_0><b11_0>chickens, quails and turkeys<b11_0/><a2_0/>) and the family Anatidae, in order <b8_0>Anseriformes<b8_0/>, commonly known as "waterfowl" and including <a4_0><b13_0>domestic ducks and domestic geese<b13_0/>.<a4_0/> Poultry also includes other birds that are killed for their meat, such as the young of pigeons (known as <b9_0>squabs<b9_0/>) <a1_0>but does not include similar wild birds hunted for sport or food and known as game.<a1_0/> The word "poultry" comes from the <b14_0>French/Norman<b14_0/> word poule, itself derived <a3_0>from the Latin word <b12_0>pullus<b12_0/>, which means <b6_0>small animal<b6_0/>.
